            <h1 id="distance-between-two-points-2d">Distance between two points (2D)</h1>

<h2 id="quick-answer">Quick Answer</h2>

<pre><code># Define the coordinates of the two points using Vector2
point1 = pygame.math.Vector2(3, 2)
point2 = pygame.math.Vector2(7, 8)

# Calculate the distance between the points
distance = point1.distance_to(point2) # Result: 7.2

# Alternatively, the distance can be represented as a vector
distance_vector = point2 - point1 # Result: Vector2(4, 6)
</code></pre>

<h2 id="pythagorean-method">Pythagorean Method</h2>

<pre><code>import math

# Define the coordinates of the two points
point1 = (3, 2)
point2 = (7, 8)

# Calculate the difference in x and y coordinates
dx = point2[0] - point1[0]
dy = point2[1] - point1[1]

# Calculate the distance
distance = math.sqrt(dx**2 + dy**2)

print("Distance between points:", distance)
</code></pre>

<h3 id="instructions">Instructions:</h3>

<ol>
<li>We import the math module, which contains the sqrt function used for calculating the square root.</li>
<li>We define two points point1 and point2 with their respective coordinates.</li>
<li>We calculate the differences in the x-coordinate (dx) and the y-coordinate (dy) between the points.</li>
<li>We use the distance formula, calculating the square root of the sum of the squares of dx and dy.</li>
<li>Finally, we print out the distance.</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Result: 7.2</strong></p>

<h3 id="shortcut-using-mathdist">SHORTCUT: Using math.dist()</h3>

<pre><code>import math

# Define the coordinates of the two points
point1 = (3, 2)
point2 = (7, 8)

# Calculate the distance
distance = math.dist(point1, point2) # NEW

print("Distance between points:", distance)
</code></pre>

<p><strong>Result: 7.2</strong></p>

<h2 id="using-vectors-pygame">Using Vectors (Pygame)</h2>

<pre><code>import pygame

# Initialize Pygame
pygame.init()

# Define the vectors for points A and B using Pygame's Vector2
A = pygame.math.Vector2(3, 2) 
B = pygame.math.Vector2(7, 8) 

# Calculate the vector from A to B
distance_vector = B - A

print("Distance vector:", distance_vector)

# Quit Pygame
pygame.quit()
</code></pre>

<h3 id="instructions-2">Instructions:</h3>

<ol>
<li>We define vectors A and B using pygame.math.Vector2. </li>
<li>We calculate the distance vector by subtracting A from B. This operation is supported directly by the Vector2 class.</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Result: [4, 6]</strong></p>

<h3 id="convert-the-vector-to-a-number-using-pythagorean-formula">Convert the vector to a number using pythagorean formula:</h3>

<p>We can convert the vector distance into a simple distance value by using the pythagorean method above:</p>

<pre><code>import pygame
import math # NEW

# Initialize Pygame
pygame.init()

# Define the vectors for points A and B using Pygame's Vector2
A = pygame.math.Vector2(3, 2) 
B = pygame.math.Vector2(7, 8) 

# Calculate the vector from A to B
distance_vector = B - A

print("Distance vector:", distance_vector)

# Provide the vector's x and y values, which represent the x and y distance, and apply pythagorean
distance = math.sqrt(distance_vector.x**2 + distance_vector.y**2) # NEW

print("Distance:", distance) # NEW

# Quit Pygame
pygame.quit()
</code></pre>

<h3 id="instructions-3">Instructions:</h3>

<ol>
<li>Provide the vector's x and y values, which represent the x and y distance, and apply the pythagorean theorem as described above. </li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Result: 7.2</strong></p>

<h3 id="shortcut-convert-the-vector-to-a-number-using-pygames-distance_to-method">SHORTCUT: Convert the vector to a number using Pygame's .distance_to() method</h3>

<p>Call .distance_to() on a vector to get the length of that vector</p>

<pre><code>import pygame

# Initialize Pygame (required for using its modules)
pygame.init()

# Define the coordinates of the two points using Vector2
point1 = pygame.math.Vector2(3, 2)
point2 = pygame.math.Vector2(7, 8)

# Calculate the distance between the points
distance = point1.distance_to(point2)

print("Distance between points:", distance)

# Quit Pygame
pygame.quit()
</code></pre>

<h3 id="instructions-4">Instructions:</h3>

<ol>
<li>Apply the .distance_to() method to the distance vector to get the length of the vector. </li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Result: 7.2</strong></p>

          
